        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-11-06 15:00:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> I think without LASSERT() I will have a warning from static analysis tool. Not sure about intention to use them or not.\n\nSorry, I cannot understand well for that, after the fixing, all the callers will pass non-NULL @lmv for the function lfsck_record_lmv(). So you want me to add \"LASSERT(lmv != NULL);\" inside the lfsck_record_lmv(), right?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3c45e916d58b85bf1abc2e38256ac7a499dccb3d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 403,
        "name": "Autotest",
        "email": "autotest@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "autotest",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-11-06 15:11:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nShadow Autotest started optional review-zfs session.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7edc581433dabbd3928f57db541ad3554bd6a1b8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 403,
        "name": "Autotest",
        "email": "autotest@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "autotest",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-11-06 15:32:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nShadow Autotest started enforced review-dne-part-1 session.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "504f29eacb77f33232cf74f39eb27f823ae0beed",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 301,
        "name": "Dmitry Eremin",
        "email": "dmitry.eremin@intel.com",
        "username": "dmiter",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-11-06 15:38:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nYes, I agree there is no NULL passed as lmv argument now. But I'm not sure that the static analysis tool is smart enough to detect this. I don't insist to insert LASSERT. I just think it make KW tool happy and can be useful to get incorrect usage of this function in the future.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "058a093f570e1b82a311c62e7661b9908229fc2d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 403,
        "name": "Autotest",
        "email": "autotest@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "autotest",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-11-06 16:30:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nShadow Autotest started enforced review-dne-part-2 session.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5c95b054d000fe8619e24e658c98a7eb20e4affa",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-11-06 23:02:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Yes, I agree there is no NULL passed as lmv argument now. But I'm not sure that the static analysis tool is smart enough to detect this. I don't insist to insert LASSERT. I just think it make KW tool happy and can be useful to get incorrect usage of this function in the future.\n\nI think the static analysis will be happy this time, because the checking \"lmv != NULL;\" has been removed by the patch, all the usages of lfsck_record_lmv() will assume that the @lmv must be non-NULL. It is unnecessary to add \"LASSERT()\" to satisfy the static analysis, because the lfsck_record_lmv() takes other pointers as parameters also, they all not use LASSERT().",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
